Package org.cloudsimplus.traces.azure

Class TracesParser

java.lang.Object
org.cloudsimplus.traces.azure.TracesParser
public class TracesParser extends Object
A parser for parsing the AzureTracesForPacking2020 dataset and other datasets that follow the same schema. For more information about the dataset follow this link: https://github.com/Azure/AzurePublicDataset/blob/master/AzureTracesForPacking2020.md
Other datasets can be used provided that they follow the same schema for the VM types (see VmTypeRecord) and VM requests (see VmRecord).
The parser expects two csv files with the VM types and VM requests, i.e., the names of the files should be vmType.csv and vm.csv, respectively. Each line in vmType.csv should follow this format: 
 
 id, vmTypeId, machineId, core, memory, hdd, ssd, nic.
Each line in vm.csv should follow this format: 
 vmId, tenantId, vmTypeId, priority, starttime, endtime.
The parser skips the first line of both files because it expects header lines.
Beyond parsing the dataset, the class is responsible for (a) processing the requests to identify VmPlacementGroup requests, and (b) creating and returning a list with all the requests, i.e., single Vm and/or VmPlacementGroup requests, in chronological order (based on their start times).
It is considered that a set of VMs belongs in a VmPlacementGroup if all the following conditions are met: 
 - the VMs share the same tenant and vmType ids, 
 - they have the same priority, and 
 - they start and end at the same times with a max difference of a predefined amount 
   of time
Since:
CloudSim Plus 7.3.2
Author:
Pavlos Maniotis

    • vmTypeRecords

      private final Map<Long,List<VmTypeRecord>> vmTypeRecords
      Each VmTypeRecord.getId() is associated with multiple resource request ratios depending on different types of servers. The resource ratios are kept in descending order according to the core utilization, i.e., the first item in the list corresponds to the ratio with the max core utilization.
